{"id":"2109.04116","submitter":"Shihori Koyama","authors":"Shihori Koyama, Daisuke Inoue, Akihisa Okada, and Hiroaki Yoshida","title":"Electro-osmotic diode based on colloidal nano-valves between double\n  membranes","comments":"Accepted for publication in Physical Review Research","journal-ref":"Physical Review Research 3 (3), 033289 (2021)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevResearch.3.033289","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.mes-hall physics.chem-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The rectification of electro-osmotic flows is important in micro/nano\nfluidics applications such as micro-pumps and energy conversion devices. Here,\nwe propose a simple electro-osmotic diode in which colloidal particles are\ncontained between two parallel membranes with different pore densities. While\nthe flow in the forward direction just pushes the colloidal particles toward\nthe high-pore-density membrane, the backward flow is blocked by the particles\nnear the low-pore-density membrane, which clog the pores. Nonequilibrium\nmolecular dynamics simulations show a strong nonlinear dependence on the\nelectric field for both the electric current and electro-osmotic flow,\nindicating diode characteristics. A mathematical model to reproduce the\nelectro-osmotic diode behavior is constructed, introducing an effective pore\ndiameter as a model for pores clogged by the colloidal particles. Good\nagreement is obtained between the proposed model with estimated parameter\nvalues and the results of direct molecular dynamics simulations. The proposed\nelectro-osmotic diode has potential application in downsized microfluidic\npumps, e.g., the pump induced under AC electric fields.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 9 Sep 2021 09:13:54 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Tue, 14 Sep 2021 02:43:06 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-10-04"}
